52236 - Zorya's Light Entropic Disintegrator This small Entropic Disintegrator is typically seen in use on Triglavian frigates and destroyers, which are able to handle the relatively minimal radiation and gravitational tidal forces the weapon generates as a side-effect of its operation.

Entropic Disintegrators draw on the tremendous power of the Triglavian singularity-based energy systems to convert exotic matter into a particle stream directed with locally generated entropic force. While powerful, the range of the weapon is limited by the attenuation of entropic forces, which dissipate critically beyond the optimal range. As a result this weapon has no falloff range.

The particle stream generates thermal and explosive reactions on impact, and the entropic forces resolve into a localized gravitational conduit that steadily increases the acceleration on the exotic particles. In effect, the weapon's damage potential increases to a maximum level as long as the particle stream is kept on the same target.

Requires exotic plasma charge ammo types: Baryon, Meson, and Tetryon.		 Precursor Weapon

52273 - The Yulai Siege YC106 On 3rd March YC106, a group of capsuleers united under the Zombie Inc corporation established a successful siege of one of the Yulai system's gates. At the time, Yulai was a key market hub and the siege caused a major disruption to the flow of trade. Standard CONCORD ships and sentry guns proved no match for the Zombie Inc fleet's remote repair capacity. The situation was resolved when the then active Jovian delegation to CONCORD intervened with their advanced technology.

After this encounter, the CONCORD Inner Circle held an emergency meeting at which the Jovian delegation agreed to provide their technology for purposes of substantially upgrading the CONCORD fleet. To this day, the CONCORD fleet's core elements remain among the most powerful in New Eden.		 Special Edition Commodities
52274 - Drone Regions YC109 In YC109, a number of sealed stargates reactivated, opening the way to an isolated group of eight regions in the New Eden cluster's north-west. Exploration of these regions by capsuleers swiftly revealed them to be infested with rogue drones and the sub-cluster of systems came to be known as the "Drone Regions" by the general population.

An official CONCORD naming committee took suggestions from capsuleer explorers for official names for the regions, which had previously been assigned alphanumeric designations. The result of the consultation was the renaming of the eight regions as follows:

H3J8-U – Cobalt Edge
6HL8-L – Outer Passage
VU-WU2 – The Spire
7-KXBJ – Etherium Reach
87-1CW – Kalevala Expanse

G5KW-3 – Oasa		 Special Edition Commodities
52275 - Jita Protest YC113 In late YC113, capsuleers staged a mass uprising against the intolerable state of affairs in New Eden's space industries and markets of the day. Protests in Jita centered on a monument in orbit of the Jita IV - Moon 4, Caldari Navy Assembly Plant, the long time center of trading in the Jita market hub.

Such was the intensity of the protestors' firepower, even the normally adamantine structure of the monument could not stand up to the impacts and it was reduced to a ruin. The ruins of the former monument to the winners of the Ruevo Aram Riddle Contest remain in place as a reminder to all of the central role of capsuleers in New Eden's space-based civilization and to the lesson that change is the only constant in human affairs. 52276 - Titanomachy YC116 The infamous Battle of B-R5RB in January YC116, also known as the "Titanomachy", resulted in the destruction of 74 Titan-class starships, after some 21 hours of fighting involving over 7,500 capsuleers. The butcher's bill was hardly restricted to the tally of Titans, which included an additional supercapital ambushed on its way to the battle proper. Some 370 dreadnoughts, 123 carriers and 13 supercarriers were also lost, with innumerable subcapital losses inflicted.

The scale and breadth of the destruction, involving 55 capsuleer alliances and 717 corporations, was such that a monument to the Titanomachy was established in the wreckage field left behind by the desperate and staggering "Bloodbath of B-R5RB".		 Special Edition Commodities
52277 - Fall of Fort Knocks YC120 At the end of YC120, roughly in the middle of the sixteenth year since the inception of independent capsuleers, the notorious Fort Knocks was destroyed in the culmination of a determined campaign to destroy the first Keepstar citadel ever built by capsuleers. The defense of Fort Knocks, anchored deep in the W-space system of J115405, was equally determined but in the final battle the Keepstar fell, ending the fortress's domination of the star system nicknamed "Rage".

Since its construction in YC118 by the Hard Knocks Citizens alliance, the Keepstar had endured through many battles but the assault by a coalition of foes lead by The Initiative chipped away at Fort Knocks's defensive network of starbases, eventually achieving local space superiority and dooming New Eden's first Keepstar to its inevitable fate. 52302 - Gila Emperor Bear SKIN (Permanent) The high lords of the ancient Caldari Raata Empire used many different sigils but one of the most famous is the sign of the Emperor Bear, believed to have been the personal sigil of Emperor K'vire III Fuukiuye of the Second Unification Realm. While the ancient histories of the Caldari are shrouded in myth and legend, this bear sigil is clearly derived from a totemic attachment to the large Emperor Bears of the southern polar archipelagos. The Fuukiuye tribes are thought to have ranged as far south as the island taigas in their remarkable migrations across the face of Caldari Prime, and surely encountered the golden-furred Emperor Bears.

It is likely that a golden bear totem was used by one of the paramount tribes and became associated with leadership over the centuries. Emperor K'vire III Fuukiuye was no doubt concerned to cement his leadership of the Raata Empire by using the symbolism. The sigil was dispensed with some two centuries later when the Fuukiuye emperors were supplanted by the Orioyoni under the leadership of Emperor Deteaas IX Orioyoni during the Third Unification. The Emperor Bear, like its northern Storm Bear cousin, remains a potent symbol for Caldari, indicative in some animist traditions of leadership that serves the collective.		 Permanent SKIN

52321 - Kikimora Red Meatgrinder SKIN (Permanent) This special commemorative nanocoating celebrates the historic Siege of C-J6MT, a major battle from the early years of capsuleer empire-building and territorial warfare.

In May YC108, the Siege of C-J6MT began as the beleaguered forces of Red Alliance formed to defend their last stronghold against their deadly foes in the "Coalition of the South". Although outnumbered, the Red Alliance pilots were determined to sell themselves dearly and based their tactics around their core defensive starbase and packs of hit-and-run Tempest-class battleships.

When Coalition forces mounted their assault, the starbase and Tempest squadrons wreaked havoc on the attackers. 86773 An Infrastructure Hub is the cornerstone of any empire's expansion into nullsec territory.

Once online, it allows the owner to cultivate the system it is placed in by applying one of the upgrades available. These upgrades range from simple improvements to a system's financial infrastructure, to defensive upgrades giving the system owner significant advantages.

To begin upgrading a star system, deploy the Infrastructure Hub close to a planet and activate an Entosis Link on the IHub until your alliance has full control.

You must be a member of a valid Capsuleer alliance to deploy and/or take control of an IHub. A maximum of one IHub may be deployed in any star system. IHubs cannot be deployed in systems under non-Capsuleer Sovereignty. IHubs cannot be deployed in Wormhole space. The weekly cost is {[numeric]cost.isk} and you will receive a bill which needs to be paid promptly to maintain the war. If the bill is not paid before it is due then the war will be cancelled.

Both sides in a war must control at least one structure in space in order to be war eligible. If either side loses their last structure, they lose their war eligibility and the war is cancelled.
The attacking side of a war must designate one highsec Upwell structure that they control as the War HQ for the conflict. If the War HQ is destroyed or removed from space the war will be cancelled.

Gneiss is a popular ore type because it holds significant volumes of three heavily used minerals, increasing its utility value. It has a quite a bit of mexallon as well as some pyerite and isogen.

This ore is a compressed and much more dense version of the original ore. 536463 This rare isotope of the mineral Isogen naturally forms stable bipyramidal crystals in the absence of the tremendous forces that typically form the more common crystal forms of Isogen, such as found in asteroids or moons. Crystalline Isogen-10 can form in space under the correct local conditions, typically requiring the abnormal gravitation fields that are found in unusual configurations of space-time topology like Abyssal Deadspace.

Isogen-10 has been determined to be useful in the construction of light but strong materials suited to varying gravitational forces and associated accelerations. It is possible this form of Isogen could be broken down into other isotopes but they would likely be unstable, and such processes would run the risk of unleashing large quantities of energy. 537223 This small Entropic Disintegrator is typically seen in use on Triglavian frigates and destroyers, which are able to handle the relatively minimal radiation and gravitational tidal forces the weapon generates as a side-effect of its operation.

Entropic Disintegrators draw on the tremendous power of the Triglavian singularity-based energy systems to convert exotic matter into a particle stream directed with locally generated entropic force. While powerful, the range of the weapon is limited by the attenuation of entropic forces, which dissipate critically beyond the optimal range. As a result this weapon has no falloff range.

The particle stream generates thermal and explosive reactions on impact, and the entropic forces resolve into a localized gravitational conduit that steadily increases the acceleration on the exotic particles. In effect, the weapon's damage potential increases to a maximum level as long as the particle stream is kept on the same target.

Requires exotic plasma charge ammo types: Baryon, Meson, and Tetryon. In effect, the weapon's damage potential increases to a maximum level as long as the particle stream is kept on the same target.

Requires either standard or advanced exotic plasma charge ammo types: Baryon, Meson, Tetryon, Mystic, and Occult. 543504 Impetus developed the Glamourex neural booster as a means to improve the charm and appeal of its holoreel stars. Generally used at a low dosage on valuable hot properties such as actors and other celebrities, Impetus does make Glamourex available at higher, possibly inadvisable potencies for those who require a rapid boost in their social standing.

Working much like the Social skill this highly potent booster provides a 75% bonus to agent, corporation and faction standing increases.

543547 The first modification of Triglavian ship design using the methods of Tech II invention and construction, the Zarmazd builds on the Collective's Rodiva-class support cruiser to create a logistics cruiser adapted for capsuleer use. The Zarmazd's design combines elements of the Amarr Guardian-class armor logistics cruiser's technology with the Triglavian ship frame, energy system and signature adaptive mutaplasmid repair system.

The Zarmazd's remote repair systems are considerably enhanced by adaptive armor-repair mutaplasmids that are used as nanite feedstock for its remote repair projectors. As the armor-repair mutaplasmid stream is able to adapt itself in real-time to specific target ship conditions far more efficiently than standard armor-repair nanites, the efficiency of armor repairing performed by the nanite stream on a given target increases over time towards a maximal repair output.

"It proved possible to adapt the ship specifications provided to incorporate some of the improvements found in our own advanced logistics cruisers. The Guardian's high-output nanofabbers were readily altered to support the production of armor-repair mutaplasmids and, while the engineering challenges were novel, the increased flow and unusual nanotopography were ultimately incorporated without great difficulty. It should be noted that any competent nanotech engineer could reproduce these adaptations using the Rodiva's specifications as a basis." – excerpt from a report from the Office of the Fabricator-General of the Imperial Navy		 The first modification of Triglavian ship design using the methods of Tech II invention and construction, the Zarmazd builds on the Collective's Rodiva-class support cruiser to create a logistics cruiser adapted for capsuleer use. 548702 The war headquarters is an Upwell Structure located somewhere in highsec space owned by the attacking side of an aggressive war. The attackers choose which of their structures to designate as the war headquarters for any given war during their initial war declaration. If the war headquarters structure is destroyed by anyone or removed from space for any reason the war will enter a 24 hour cooldown and then end. If a war ends due to the destruction or removal of the war headquarters, the former attacking organization will be unable to declare new wars against the former defending organization for two weeks. 548999 The high lords of the ancient Caldari Raata Empire used many different sigils but one of the most famous is the sign of the Emperor Bear, believed to have been the personal sigil of Emperor K'vire III Fuukiuye of the Second Unification Realm. While the ancient histories of the Caldari are shrouded in myth and legend, this bear sigil is clearly derived from a totemic attachment to the large Emperor Bears of the southern polar archipelagos. The Fuukiuye tribes are thought to have ranged as far south as the island taigas in their remarkable migrations across the face of Caldari Prime, and surely encountered the golden-furred Emperor Bears.

It is likely that a golden bear totem was used by one of the paramount tribes and became associated with leadership over the centuries. Emperor K'vire III Fuukiuye was no doubt concerned to cement his leadership of the Raata Empire by using the symbolism. The sigil was dispensed with some two centuries later when the Fuukiuye emperors were supplanted by the Orioyoni under the leadership of Emperor Deteaas IX Orioyoni during the Third Unification. The Emperor Bear, like its northern Storm Bear cousin, remains a potent symbol for Caldari, indicative in some animist traditions of leadership that serves the collective. 549061 On 3rd March YC106, a group of capsuleers united under the Zombie Inc corporation established a successful siege of one of the Yulai system's gates. At the time, Yulai was a key market hub and the siege caused a major disruption to the flow of trade. Standard CONCORD ships and sentry guns proved no match for the Zombie Inc fleet's remote repair capacity. The situation was resolved when the then active Jovian delegation to CONCORD intervened with their advanced technology.

After this encounter, the CONCORD Inner Circle held an emergency meeting at which the Jovian delegation agreed to provide their technology for purposes of substantially upgrading the CONCORD fleet. To this day, the CONCORD fleet's core elements remain among the most powerful in New Eden. 549063 In YC109, a number of sealed stargates reactivated, opening the way to an isolated group of eight regions in the New Eden cluster's north-west. Exploration of these regions by capsuleers swiftly revealed them to be infested with rogue drones and the sub-cluster of systems came to be known as the "Drone Regions" by the general population.

An official CONCORD naming committee took suggestions from capsuleer explorers for official names for the regions, which had previously been assigned alphanumeric designations. The result of the consultation was the renaming of the eight regions as follows:

549064 In late YC113, capsuleers staged a mass uprising against the intolerable state of affairs in New Eden's space industries and markets of the day. Protests in Jita centered on a monument in orbit of the Jita IV - Moon 4, Caldari Navy Assembly Plant, the long time center of trading in the Jita market hub.

Such was the intensity of the protestors' firepower, even the normally adamantine structure of the monument could not stand up to the impacts and it was reduced to a ruin. The ruins of the former monument to the winners of the Ruevo Aram Riddle Contest remain in place as a reminder to all of the central role of capsuleers in New Eden's space-based civilization and to the lesson that change is the only constant in human affairs. 549065 The infamous Battle of B-R5RB in January YC116, also known as the "Titanomachy", resulted in the destruction of 74 Titan-class starships, after some 21 hours of fighting involving over 7,500 capsuleers. The butcher's bill was hardly restricted to the tally of Titans, which included an additional supercapital ambushed on its way to the battle proper. Some 370 dreadnoughts, 123 carriers and 13 supercarriers were also lost, with innumerable subcapital losses inflicted.

The scale and breadth of the destruction, involving 55 capsuleer alliances and 717 corporations, was such that a monument to the Titanomachy was established in the wreckage field left behind by the desperate and staggering "Bloodbath of B-R5RB". 549066 At the end of YC120, roughly in the middle of the sixteenth year since the inception of independent capsuleers, the notorious Fort Knocks was destroyed in the culmination of a determined campaign to destroy the first Keepstar citadel ever built by capsuleers. The defense of Fort Knocks, anchored deep in the W-space system of J115405, was equally determined but in the final battle the Keepstar fell, ending the fortress's domination of the star system nicknamed "Rage".

Since its construction in YC118 by the Hard Knocks Citizens alliance, the Keepstar had endured through many battles but the assault by a coalition of foes lead by The Initiative chipped away at Fort Knocks's defensive network of starbases, eventually achieving local space superiority and dooming New Eden's first Keepstar to its inevitable fate. 549084 Released in YC121, this special edition entry in the Eico augmentation series celebrates Capsuleer Day XVI.

Environmental information capture overlays go several steps beyond somatosensory meshes and considerably enhance the sensory capabilities of those "wearing" such extensive facial augmentations. While this level of cybernetics can hardly be masked by mere nanocoatings there is still considerable scope for working in decorative elements.

Eico augmentations include systems that improve the connection between an augmented individual's consciousness and their nervous-emotional responses. However, these more extensive and elaborate information capture and processing systems hugely increase the types and range of environmental information that can be absorbed by an individual.

Whether sipping cocktails in the zero-g bars of Caille, or ripping apart the sputtering remains of a pirate vessel with your guns in nullsec, one thing will be certain: those who see your face will have it etched into their memory forever. 549271 This special commemorative nanocoating celebrates the historic Siege of C-J6MT, a major battle from the early years of capsuleer empire-building and territorial warfare.

In May YC108, the Siege of C-J6MT began as the beleaguered forces of Red Alliance formed to defend their last stronghold against their deadly foes in the "Coalition of the South". Although outnumbered, the Red Alliance pilots were determined to sell themselves dearly and based their tactics around their core defensive starbase and packs of hit-and-run Tempest-class battleships.

When Coalition forces mounted their assault, the starbase and Tempest squadrons wreaked havoc on the attackers. So high was the butcher's bill racked up by the Red Alliance starbase it was given the nickname "The Meatgrinder" by the defenders. Ultimately, the Siege of C-J6MT was won by Red Alliance and proved a turning point in the conflict with the Coalition of the South. 549419 In a declared war, members of each organization may freely attack members of the opposing organization without penalty. Wars contain a 24 hour warning period before they begin so that both sides may prepare for the conflict, and when wars end they enter a 24 hour cooldown during which shooting may legally continue so that both sides can prepare for peace.
Aggressive wars are formally declared by one attacking organization against one defending organization, while mutual wars are agreed upon by both sides equally.

Aggressive wars can end if a surrender offer is accepted, if the attacking side fails to pay their weekly war bill, if the defending side loses their last structure in space, or if the attacker loses their war headquarters structure.
Wars will be inherited whenever corporations leave an alliance that is at war, or when a defending corporation joins an alliance. These inherited wars have all the same requirements as other wars, and if they do not meet any of the requirements (including war eligibility) they will enter the 24 hour cooldown and then end.

Corporations and alliances are eligible to participate in aggressive wars if they control at least one structure in space. If a corporation or alliance wishes to avoid having wars declared against them, they can choose not to deploy a structure in space.
Aggressive wars require a recurring ISK payment by the attacking side and the attacking organization must designate an Upwell Structure they control in high security space as the war headquarters for any given war.
Mutual wars do not require ISK payments or structures, can only be started by mutual agreement of both sides, and can be ended by either side at any time with 24 hours warning. 549420 ISK fees for aggressive wars must be paid by the attacking organization in order to continue the war. The initial war declaration cost represents the pre-payment for the first week of the war, and the attacking side will then receive a bill for the second week of the war that they can pay anytime before the beginning of that second week.

War bills will appear in the bills payable section of the corporation wallet approximately one week before they are due, and can be paid manually or set to auto-pay as desired.
If war bills are not paid on time, the war will enter a 24 cooldown period and then end.

Mutual wars do not require ISK payments.		 ISK fees for aggressive wars must be paid by the attacking organization in order to continue the war. 549421 The defenders in a war may choose to seek assistance in the war and open itself for ally offers. Potential allies can then offer their services to the defenders either for free or for an ISK fee. If an ally offer is accepted, there will be a 4 hour warning period after which the ally organization will enter a state of war with the attacking organization for two weeks.

Potential ally corporations or alliances will need to be war eligible at the start of their ally period, although losing their structures will not eject them from the ally state early.
The first active ally in any given war does not have any CONCORD ISK fees above and beyond the fee requested by the ally. The second active ally requires a CONCORD fee of 10 million ISK above and beyond the ISK fee requested by the ally, and this CONCORD fee doubles for each additional ally beyond the second.

Allies are not available for the attacking side of a war, or for either side of a mutual war.

Although allies are able to assist the defenders by shooting and otherwise disrupting the attackers, allies will be subject to the normal third party penalties if they use remote assistance modules to repair or boost members of the defending organization or other allies. 549422 Mutual wars are started through an invite/acceptance system, which requires consent from both sides. Mutual wars allow the same free and unimpeded combat between the two organizations in empire space as aggressive wars, without the war eligibility, war headquarters, or ISK fee requirements of an aggressive war.

Mutual wars may be ended by either party at will, with the standard 24 hour cooldown before combat stops.

Allies are not available in mutual wars.		 Mutual wars are started through an invite/acceptance system, which requires consent from both sides. 549423 Corporations and alliances must be war eligible to participate in aggressive wars as an attacker, defender, or to begin their period as an ally. If the last structure owned by a corporation or alliance leaves space or is destroyed, any aggressive wars in which they are the attacker or defender will enter a 24 hour cooldown and then end.

The following types of player-owned structures count towards war eligibility: All Upwell Structures (including Upwell FLEX structures), starbase control towers, customs offices and customs office gantries, infrastructure hubs and territorial control units.
Structures in any area of space count towards war eligibility.
If any member corporation of an alliance owns at least one structure in space, the whole alliance becomes war eligible.

Attackers must designate a specific Upwell Structure that they own in highsec space as their war headquarters for a given aggressive war. If this war headquarters structure is destroyed or removed from space for any reason during the war, the war will enter a 24 hour cooldown and then end. If a war ends due to the removal of the war headquarters, the former attacking organization will not be able to declare a new war against the former defending organization for two weeks.		 Corporations and alliances must be war eligible to participate in aggressive wars as an attacker, defender, or to begin their period as an ally. If the last structure owned by a corporation or alliance leaves space or is destroyed, any aggressive wars in which they are the attacker or defender will enter a 24 hour cooldown and then end.

The following types of player-owned structures count towards war eligibility: All Upwell Structures (including Upwell FLEX structures), starbase control towers, customs offices and customs office gantries, infrastructure hubs and territorial control units.
Structures in any area of space count towards war eligibility.

549424 Enforced peace periods are created whenever wars end because of an accepted surrender offer or the destruction/removal of a war headquarters structure.

If a war ends through an accepted surrender offer, then neither the former attacking or defending organizations from that war will be able to declare new wars against their counterparts from that war for two weeks.

If a war ends through the destruction or removal of a war headquarters structure, then the former attacking organization of that war will be unable to declare new wars against the former defending organization. In this case the enforced peace is only one-way and the former defenders are free to declare new wars against the former attackers if they wish. 549539 This large Entropic Disintegrator is only seen in use on Triglavian battleships, these massive ships being capable of managing the considerable radiation and enormous gravitational tidal forces the weapon generates. At the energy levels of this superheavy weapon system, the tidal forces are such that special systems are built into the ship to counteract them.

Entropic Disintegrators draw on the tremendous power of the Triglavian singularity-based energy systems to convert exotic matter into a particle stream directed with locally generated entropic force. While powerful, the range of the weapon is limited by the attenuation of entropic forces, which dissipate critically beyond the optimal range. As a result this weapon has no falloff range.

The particle stream generates thermal and explosive reactions on impact, and the entropic forces resolve into a localized gravitational conduit that steadily increases the acceleration on the exotic particles. In effect, the weapon's damage potential increases to a maximum level as long as the particle stream is kept on the same target.

Requires exotic plasma charge ammo types: Baryon, Meson, and Tetryon. 549902 Standings are a measure of reputation, and affect your access to missions and other content. Successfully completing missions for an agent will increase your standings with:

- The agent personally
- The agent's corporation
- Their corporation's faction

Likewise, failing missions and destroying a faction's property will reduce your standings with them and their affiliates. Note: gaining standings with a faction will also improve your standings with their factional allies, while reducing standings with their enemies. So choose your allies wisely!

When deciding to offer you missions, agents will look at the the highest standings you have achieved with either their corporation or faction.
